<subSubSection id="C309EEC62F70FFFB4EAFF9B3FB2CF939" pageId="10" pageNumber="161" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BACBD4D2F70FFFB4EAFF9B3FB2CF939" blockId="10.[151,1436,1407,1685]" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">
<emphasis id="B967615F2F70FFFB4EAFF9B3FE29F984" bold="true" box="[199,502,1551,1576]" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Distribution and habitat.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C13C6CE2F70FFFB4C68F9B3FD04F984" box="[512,731,1551,1576]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Bachia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="161" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="scolecoides">
<emphasis id="B967615F2F70FFFB4C68F9B3FD04F984" box="[512,731,1551,1576]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Bachia scolecoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is endemic to southern Brazilian 
<taxonomicName id="4C13C6CE2F70FFFB4A0CF9B3FB05F984" box="[1124,1242,1551,1576]" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Meliolaceae" genus="Amazonia" kingdom="Fungi" order="Meliolales" pageId="10" pageNumber="195" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">Amazonia</taxonomicName>
, restricted to the area between the Juruena and Xingu rivers (
<figureCitation id="1328A1C82F70FFFB4CE4F988FD0DF9E0" box="[652,722,1588,1613]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1113,1135]" captionTargetBox="[154,1434,189,1086]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,179,1091]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Distribution of examined material of Amapasaurus tetradactylus, B. panoplia, B. peruana, B. pyburni, B. remota, B. scolecoides, and B. trisanale. Records of Bachia didactyla and B. scaea were obtained from the literature." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/581978/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). It is known from the states of 
<collectingRegion id="49D773AF2F70FFFB4A28F988FBADF9E0" box="[1088,1138,1588,1612]" country="Brazil" name="Para" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Pará</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion id="49D773AF2F70FFFB4AC3F989FA9EF9E0" box="[1195,1345,1588,1612]" country="Brazil" name="Mato Grosso" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Mato Grosso</collectingRegion>
. 
<taxonomicName id="4C13C6CE2F70FFFB4B24F988FEC7F9DC" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Bachia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="161" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="scolecoides">
<emphasis id="B967615F2F70FFFB4B24F988FEC7F9DC" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Bachia scolecoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is fossorial, and according to museum records it inhabits open vegetation enclaves. Despite its description more than 50 years ago, natural history information about 
<taxonomicName id="4C13C6CE2F70FFFB4DCFF9C1FB98F939" box="[935,1095,1660,1685]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Bachia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="161" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="scolecoides">
<emphasis id="B967615F2F70FFFB4DCFF9C1FB98F939" box="[935,1095,1660,1685]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">B. scolecoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is still lacking.
</paragraph>
